# WebStrike - My First CyberDefender Lab

**Platform:** CyberDefender | **Difficulty:** Easy
**Category:** Network Forensics | **Date:** May 2026

## What Was This About?
Someone uploaded a malicious file to a company web server.
The network team captured the traffic and my job was to 
dig through the PCAP file and figure out what happened.

## Tools I Used
- Wireshark (to analyze the network traffic)
- ipgeolocation.io (to track where the attacker was from)

## What I Did
I started by opening the PCAP file in Wireshark. I filtered 
for HTTP GET requests to find the attacker's IP address, then 
looked it up on ipgeolocation.io which showed the attack came 
from Tianjin, China.

Next I looked at the HTTP headers and found the attacker's 
User-Agent which told me they were running Linux with Firefox.

I then filtered for HTTP POST requests which is how file 
uploads happen. Following the HTTP stream showed me a file 
called image.jpg.php was uploaded — a classic trick where 
attackers disguise a PHP web shell as an image.

The web shell was uploaded to /reviews/uploads/ and was used 
to open a reverse shell back to the attacker on port 8080.
Finally I found they were trying to steal the passwd file.

## What I Found
- Attack came from Tianjin, China
- Attacker used Linux with Firefox 115
- Web shell uploaded: image.jpg.php
- Upload folder: /reviews/uploads/
- Reverse shell port: 8080
- File they tried to steal: passwd

## What I Learned
This was my first time analyzing a real attack in Wireshark.
I learned how attackers disguise malicious files, how reverse 
shells work, and how to spot data exfiltration in network 
traffic. Filtering HTTP streams in Wireshark was really 
eye-opening.
